 at Obajana. The partnership meeting session held to control the challenges of FSW activities with LDD activities. The meeting was conducted to bring the FSW and LDD very close. A lot of issues are discussed about FSW right, human right and their relationship with community.</p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PROJECT OBJECTIVE 9:</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>FEMALE SEX WORKERS (FSW) FOCUS GROUP DISCUSSION SESSION </strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; FSW Focus Group Discussion session held in all FSW projects sites, Ankpa LGA, Idah LGA and Ofu LGA was conducted by the project team in conjunction with the trained peer educators and the LACA officers from each LGA.&nbsp; Each peer educator brought along their selected cohort members whom they have started meeting at cohort sessions. It was successful as it opened door for the LACA officer to participation. Apart from the peers educator and RWEYDF team, the LACA officer are also giving chance to facilitate the session. Condom messaging and demonstration and requested for condoms which were distributed with HIV service.</p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;PROJECT OBJECTIVE 10: </strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>CAPACITY BUILDING FOR HEALTH WORKERS</strong></p>\n\n<p>RWEYDF conducted Capacity Building for Health Workers on Syndrome Management in all our project sites in Ankpa LGA, Idah LGA, Ofu LGA and Lokoja LGA. It was a successful partnership meeting session with some selected health workers across all our project sites. The health workers were thought syndrome management on STI, HIV and AIDS infection. The participants were ushered expertly and systematically into their own world through self appraisal and began to see things they never thought of before. Among others, they were taught about HIV, what it is, mode of infection and transmission, mode of prevention, HIV counseling and testing, stigma and discrimination, as well as orphan and vulnerable children.&nbsp; Others include the human anatomy, the reproductive system, stages of human development, self esteem and other life skills, value system, STI and the relationship between all they have learnt with HIV infection and prevention.&nbsp; All these opened up a new world view to understanding the issue of HIV to them. Crucially and very important, they were taught condom messaging and demonstration as well as cohort session facilitation. Practical sessions were held to give each of them the opportunity to demonstrate how condom is used as well as to facilitate the session.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;PROJECT OBJECTIVE 11: </strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>CAPACITY BUILDING FOR FSW</strong></p>\n\n<p>RWEYDF conducted Capacity Building for Female Sex Workers on make-up training for five days in Lokoja. The training was facilitating by Zozas Builty and Make-up Saloon, Lokoja. The participant was selection from all our project sites in Ankpa LGA, Idah LGA and Ofu LGA. It was a successful training session with some selected female sex workers across all our project sites. The FSW were thought differences type of make-up and saloon style for the period of the training in Lokoja. The participants were ushered expertly and systematically into their own world through self appraisal and began to see things they never thought of before. Among others, they were taught about the management of the training, what is the market strategies, mode of advertising the product and ways of making customers, customer relationship between all they have learnt.&nbsp; All these opened up a new world view to understanding the issue of make-up to them. Crucially and very important, they were taught time management as well as business feasibility study in any community. Practical sessions were held to give each of them the opportunity to demonstrate on how to do make-up.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>CHALLINGES: </strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The lectures started about one hour behind schedule as we had to wait for participant who was held up by the heavy traffic.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PROJECT OBJECTIVE 12:</strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>NETWORKING &amp; PARTNERSHIP MEETING</strong></p>\n\n<p>The FSW networking and partnership meeting with hotel managers and the police in the project sites was successfully conducted. A successful networking and partnership meeting of FSW with hotel managers and the police held at the three FSW project site from Ankpa LGA at Liberty hotel, Idah LGA at Partners hotel and Ofu LGA at Concord hotel, Itobe. The networking and partnership meeting held to control the challenges of FSW activities with hotel managers and the police. The meeting was conducted to bring the community leaders and police very close. A lot of issue are discussed about FSW right and their relationship with community and police.</p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PROJECT OBJECTIVE 13: </strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT</strong><strong> </strong></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The RWEYDF conduct community engagement in all the project site for community involvement. Community engagement session was successfully running with hotel managers, community leaders, FSW leaders and driver&rsquo;s union leaders all from Ankpa LGA, Idah LGA, Ofu LGA and Lokoja LGA. A community engagement session was successful as it opened the door for community participation. The people realize that the project has had positive impact.&nbsp; Hence, they are ready to take it over. The community engagement session held to striating the relationship between the community leaders and all concerning groups.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; MANAGEMENT ACTIVITIES</strong></p>\n\n<p>The management of RWEYDF appoints two of its staff M&amp;E Officer Mr. Lamidi .E. Muhammed and Mr. Yahaya Abubakar programme coordinator to attend five days training on MPPI &amp; DHIS. The training to bust the capacity of the staff on national HIV prevention programme and to provide programme managers and implementers with skills on how to use the national HIV prevention routine monitoring and train M&amp;E focal persons from HAF CSOs on the M&amp;E of prevention, care and support and OVC programme. The training also equip participants with skills in promoting the culture of data use among HAF CSOs, SSOs and other relevant stakeholders at the state, LGA and community levels.&nbsp; As earlier agreed with the KOSACA, SSOs have been appointed to monitor the activities of CSOs in the field, there are with us in the field this month activities for their own contribution and comment.</p>\n\n<p>RWEYDF M&amp;E officer Mr. Lamidi .E. Muhammed attend a one day SACA/CSOs/IPs/NEPWHAN Forum organized by Kogi State Agency for the Control of Aids (KOSACA) on Thursday 7th May, 2015 at Liberty Hotel, Lokoja to discusses way forward and challenges.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;He also attends another one day SACA/HAF GRANTEES QUARTERLY REVIEW meeting on Thursday 28th May, 2015 at Rock and Garden Hotel, Lokoja call by KOSACA to build capacity of CSOs to be in the right pat for the HAF project.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; CHALLENGES AND PROGRAM RESPONSES TO THESE</strong></p>\n\n<p>Transportation logistics and risk of being on the accident-prone highway on a daily basis is a major challenge, as each journey leaves one completely drained emotionally and destabilized for several hours.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; CONCLUSION:</strong></p>\n\n<p>With the intensive activities conducted by RWEYDF for FSW &amp; LDD the program has taken a definite shape for a successful intervention. RWEYDF put everything in please to achieve it target of the project.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; RECOMMENDATIONS:</strong></p>\n\n<p>The people realize that the project has had positive impact.&nbsp; Hence, they are ready to take it over.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n",
